# Worker Conventions

## Structure

- Each job type gets its own file: `jobs/llm-completion.job.ts`, `jobs/audit-write.job.ts`.
- Queue definitions in `queues/` — one queue per job category.
- Jobs are pure functions: take payload → do work → return result. No HTTP or WebSocket.

## Job Design

```typescript
// ✅ Job processor pattern
export const processLlmCompletion = async (job: Job<LlmCompletionPayload>) => {
  const { conversationId, messages, providerId } = job.data;
  // ... process and publish result to Redis pub/sub
};
```

- Jobs must be **idempotent** — safe to retry on failure.
- Include all needed data in the job payload. Don't rely on external state that may change.
- Set `attempts` and `backoff` strategy on every queue.

## Error Handling

- Throw errors to trigger BullMQ retry. Don't silently swallow failures.
- Use `job.log()` for progress tracking visible in the admin dashboard.
- Dead-letter failed jobs after max retries — log to audit for admin review.

## Queues

| Queue | Purpose | Retry |
|-------|---------|-------|
| `llm-completion` | LLM streaming calls | 3 attempts, exponential backoff |
| `audit-write` | Async audit log persistence | 5 attempts, fixed 1s delay |
| `webhook-delivery` | Outbound webhook POST | 3 attempts, exponential backoff |
| `auto-title` | Generate conversation titles | 2 attempts, no backoff |
